summaries.title: Developing Leadership Confidence Through Robotics Projects
summaries.summaryText: Ethan described how leading design sprints in the robotics club refined his communication and teamwork skills. He recognized his relative advantage from prior exposure to engineering through his family, and expressed an interest in mentoring peers with less background experience. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Leadership and Mentorship in Engineering Design Projects
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah described how leading senior design teams strengthened her confidence in project management and technical problem-solving. She reflected on mentorship as a core component of her academic identity, often supporting younger women of color navigating engineering culture. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Transition from High School to University-Level Engineering
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Building Community Through Cultural Organizations
summaries.summaryText: Participation in SHPE and campus cultural centers provided Maria a sense of belonging and identity affirmation. These communities offered emotional support and mentorship that she could not easily find in her department. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Transition from High School to University-Level Engineering
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Navigating Gender Bias in Research Environments
summaries.summaryText: She recounted experiences where her technical contributions were overlooked and strategies she used to assert confidence. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Research and Cultural Expectations
summaries.summaryText: Priya balanced heavy research commitments with cultural obligations, feeling pressure to excel as a first-gen Indian-American student in tech. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Representation and Visibility in Engineering Spaces
summaries.summaryText: She emphasized how few Black women were visible in faculty and leadership roles, describing representation as both motivating and emotionally taxing. Her NSBE involvement offered vital affirmation and a platform to advocate for equity. [Part 2/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Joined the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers during her first semester to find community and mentorship. [Timeline 1]
Served as a teaching assistant for an introductory design course, emphasizing peer inclusivity. [Timeline 4]
Completed internship at a manufacturing firm where he recognized gender imbalance in leadership positions. [Timeline 2]
Struggled during his first programming course, leading him to seek help from tutoring and peers. [Timeline 3]
Struggled during his first programming course, leading him to seek help from tutoring and peers. [Timeline 2]
Faced academic probation warning after struggling with Calculus II due to lack of tutoring access. [Timeline 4]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniel’s experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Family Expectations and Cultural Motivation
themes.description: Cultural values around family honor and sacrifice serve both as motivation and a source of pressure for first-generation Vietnamese-American students pursuing STEM. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 2]

themes.title: First-Generation Adaptation to STEM Rigor
themes.description: Luis’s story demonstrates resilience through peer and cultural support. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Intersection of Culture and Academic Identity
themes.description: Cultural expectations of excellence create dual pressure for first-gen students in technical majors. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Cultural Representation as a Source of Motivation
themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Maria’s sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 4]

quotes.quoteText: No one in my family went to college, so I didn’t even know how office hours worked my first semester. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria describing her initial confusion with academic expectations as a first-gen student.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Aaliyah describing the advocacy work tied to her leadership role.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

quotes.quoteText: When our robotics team included people from different majors, the solutions got way more creative. It wasn’t just engineers thinking like engineers. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Ethan on the value of diverse collaboration.

quotes.quoteText: Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Daniel describing peer mentorship as a belonging intervention.

quotes.quoteText: It took me a year to realize struggling is normal — not a sign that I’m not supposed to be here. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Daniel describing the turning point after joining peer mentoring programs.

quotes.quoteText: I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship — it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria discussing gaps in support infrastructure.

quotes.quoteText: You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Sarah connecting wellness and academic productivity.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Daniel discussing his sense of imposter syndrome in engineering coursework.

quotes.quoteText: When our robotics team included people from different majors, the solutions got way more creative. It wasn’t just engineers thinking like engineers. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Ethan on the value of diverse collaboration.

quotes.quoteText: You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Sarah connecting wellness and academic productivity.

quotes.quoteText: My parents don’t really understand what I study, but they tell everyone I’m going to be an engineer — that means a lot, but it’s also scary. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on parental expectations and emotional weight of being first-gen.

quotes.quoteText: You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Sarah connecting wellness and academic productivity.

quotes.quoteText: If I can use my position to make sure everyone gets a fair shot in our projects, that’s what good leadership looks like. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Ethan describing inclusive team leadership philosophy.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Broaden Access to Early Engineering Exposure Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Ethan’s reflection highlights unequal early access to STEM exposure. Partnering with local schools and community programs can help level the playing field for underrepresented groups. [Extended 2]
actionItems: Create summer bridge programs for high school students
Offer needs-based scholarships for pre-college engineering camps

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Integrate cultural competence into departmental events

areasForImprovement.description: Provide stronger academic transition support for first-generation students entering engineering. [Extended 4]

Include advocacy experience in leadership award criteria
